Now I see how it works. Let me look at how the related old implementation handles the context switch with the schedMutex.

Looking at nth_changeContext in nthread.c:
```c
void nth_changeContext(nThread thisTh, nThread nextTh) {
  CHECK_CRITICAL("nth_ChangeContext")

  if (thisTh!=NULL) {
    thisTh->allocCoreId= -1;
  }

  if (nextTh->allocCoreId!=-1)
    nFatalError("nth_changeContext", "Next thread is already allocated\n");

  nth_contextChanges++;

  ...

  nextTh->allocCoreId= nth_coreId();
  nth_setSelf(nextTh);

  nextTh->lastTh= thisTh;
  if (thisTh==NULL)
    setcontext(&nextTh->uctx);
  else if (thisTh!=nextTh) {
    swapcontext(&thisTh->uctx, &nextTh->uctx);
    nth_cleanBuriedThread(&thisTh->lastTh);
  }
}
```

The swapcontext saves the current thread's context (including its stack and registers) and restores the next thread's context. When the current thread is swapped out, the schedMutex is still locked. When the next thread resumes, it was previously swapped out while holding the schedMutex. So the schedMutex is "transferred" from one thread to the next.

But wait, with multi-core, the schedMutex is a GLOBAL mutex. If thread A holds it and suspends, thread B on a different core can't acquire it.

Actually, I think the answer is that with FCFS multi-core scheduling, only one thread can be in a critical section at any time (globally). Threads are scheduled on different cores, but the scheduler mutex ensures mutual exclusion.

When thread A suspends (holding the schedMutex), it yields the core. The core then picks the next READY thread (thread C) from the ready queue. But thread C can't enter a critical section because the schedMutex is locked.

