Actually, I think I see it now. In nth_rrSchedule (or nth_fcfsSchedule), the schedule function is called INSIDE a critical section (the caller holds the schedMutex). But inside schedule, when a context switch happens, the schedMutex is STILL HELD by the current thread. When the next thread runs, it's running inside ITS OWN critical section, which was previously active when it was suspended.

