The zip command times out because the tests take too long. The issue is that `make zip` runs `make run-san`, `make run-g`, and `make run` sequentially, and each takes time. With the timeout of 70 seconds, it doesn't complete.

Let me modify the approach. Instead of running `make zip`, let me just generate the required files manually - `resultados.txt` and `subasta.zip` - by capturing the test output separately.

Actually, looking at the Makefile's `zip` target:
```makefile
zip:
	@if grep -P '\t' $(PROB).c ; then echo "Su archivo $(PROB).c contiene tabs.  Reemplacelos por espacios en blanco!" ; false ; else true; fi
	@rm -f resultados.txt $(PROB).zip
	@echo "Sistema operativo utilizado" > resultados.txt
	@uname -a >> resultados.txt
	@cat resultados.txt
	@echo ==== run-san ==== | tee -a resultados.txt
	@$(MAK) -B run-san | tee -a resultados.txt
	@echo ==== run-g ==== | tee -a resultados.txt
	@$(MAK) -B run-g | tee -a resultados.txt
	@echo ==== run ==== | tee -a resultados.txt
	@$(MAK) -B run | tee -a resultados.txt
	@echo ==== zip ====
	zip -r $(PROB).zip resultados.txt $(PROB).c
	@echo "Archivo $(PROB).zip generado"
	@echo "Revise que contiene su ultima version de $(PROB).c"
```

It runs all three tests sequentially with `make -B`. The run-san takes about 60s, run-g takes about 60s, and run takes about 30s. Total is about 2.5 minutes.

Let me just run each test separately and then create the zip file.
